runtime-optimize-memory-access:
> I guess it's one of those cases when safe code doesn't read better than unsafe

It is because of we have not designed safe APIs that make this kind of code look good.

I think that that best you can do using existing .NET APIs is approximation of "eat the span" pattern that's idiomatic in golang:
```csharp
while (span.Length >= 8)
{
   ulong v = BitConverter.ToInt64(span);

   ...

   span = span.Slice(8);
}
```

New APIs can make it look better:
```
while (BitConverter.TryRead(span, out long v))
{
   ...

   span = span.Slice(8);
}
```

Another alternative is to introduce iterators that are idiomatic in Rust:
```
// Rust equivalent is for chunk in data.array_chunks::<8>()
foreach (long v in span.IterateAsInt64())
{
...
}
```

